Context:¶

Can you differentiate a weed from a crop seedling?

The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment.

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages

To implement the techniques learnt as a part of the course

In [8]:
# As we have seen above, before we process the image, we should get the cleaner representation of the image. In other words, the noise should be removed from the images. 
# Here we will suppress the background and focus on the plant only. To achieve this, we can extrcat the green region from the image that only represents the plant itself. 
# I am assuming no background contains green color and this will help us get the clear representation of the plants only and make accurate predictions.

# Define helper function that pre process the image and get rid of the background

def process_extract_images(img):
  # Initialize Gaussian Blurring
  gblur = cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (5,5), 0)

  # Steps teaken to extract green color from the image
  # 1. Get the image in the hsv format
  # 2. Since Green color hue ranges from 24 to 76, we will use this values as start and end to determine right color spectrum
  # 3. Select the pixels only greater than 0 (represents only green region)
  # 4. Use the above mast to retrirve green image

  hsv_format = cv2.cvtColor(gblur, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
  start_green = (24,40,40)
  end_green = (76,255,255)
  green_mask = cv2.inRange(hsv_format,start_green,end_green)

  finalImg = np.zeros_like(img, np.uint8)
  finalImg[green_mask > 0] = img[green_mask > 0]
  return finalImg
In [9]:
# Process images and get the without background and Gaussian blurred images
processedImgs = []
for img in imgs:
  processed = process_extract_images(img)
  processedImgs.append(processed)

# Change the data type to float as we will be dividing by 255
processedImgs = np.asarray(processedImgs, dtype=np.float32)
processedImgs /= 255.0

In [16]:
# Build model using Sequential API
model = Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(32, 3, input_shape=(128,128,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2,2)))

# Flatten the data for the input to Dense network
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(BatchNormalization())

# Initialize Dense network
model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer='he_normal', use_bias=False))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Activation('elu'))

model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer='he_normal', use_bias=False))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Activation('elu'))

# Output layer with Softmax function
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Optimizers
optmzr = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optmzr, metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()

Observations:¶

  • Here all the parameters have been chosen after too many trials and best have been selected that yields best output.
  • As seen above, I have used combination of COnvilution and Max pooling layer to create the CNN model.
  • First Conv2D layer has 32 feature maps and applied to original image with 3x3 filter.
  • The ideal approach of increasing feature maps is followed, this is used to make a gread trade off for reducing picture size because of pooling layer.
  • Four Conv2D layers have been used that is followed by Dense network. Here , RELU activation function is being used.
  • 2 Dense layer has been used to make Fully connected layer. First Dense layer has 64 neurons which would have input from preceeding Conv2D layer.
  • Second Dense layer has 32 neurons.
  • Each Dense layer is followed by BatchNormalization to normalize the picture intensity and then followed by Activation function ELU which yields best result.
  • At last, Adam optimizer with learning rate of 0.001 is used and loss function is categorical_crossentropy is used as this is multi classification problem.
In [17]:
# Early Stoppping and Model Checkpoint for the Model filt call backs

class CustomEarlyStopping(Callback):
    def __init__(self):
        super(CustomEarlyStopping, self).__init__()
        self.best_weights = None
        
    def on_train_begin(self, logs=None):
        # The epoch the training stops at.
        self.stopped_epoch = 0
  
        self.best_val_accuracy = 0.90
        self.best_accuracy = 0.90

    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None): 
        val_accuracy=logs.get('val_accuracy')
        acc=logs.get('accuracy')

        
        if np.greater(val_accuracy, self.best_val_accuracy) and np.greater(acc, self.best_accuracy):
            self.best_val_accuracy = val_accuracy
            self.best_accuracy = acc
            self.stopped_epoch = epoch
            self.model.stop_training = True
            # Record the best weights if current results is better (less).
            self.best_weights = self.model.get_weights()
        else:
            return
                
    def on_train_end(self, logs=None):
        if self.stopped_epoch > 0:
            print("Epoch %05d: early stopping" % (self.stopped_epoch + 1))
